.TH CAFFEINATE 1 "2026-07-06" "caffeinate" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
caffeinate \- prevent the system from sleeping
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B caffeinate
.RB [ \-dismu ]
.RB [ \-t
.IR seconds ]
.RB [ \-w
.IR pid ]
.RB [ \-v ]
.RI [ command " [" args ...]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B caffeinate
prevents the system (and optionally the display) from going to sleep while it
runs.  It is a Linux clone of the macOS
.BR caffeinate (8)
command and is deliberately
.B init\-system agnostic:
it speaks D\-Bus directly via libdbus and never links against or invokes
systemd.
.PP
Its primary backend is the freedesktop
.B login1
manager interface, implemented by
.B systemd\-logind
on systemd distributions and by
.B elogind
on non\-systemd distributions (Void, Devuan, Artix, Gentoo/OpenRC, ...).  If no
login1 provider is present it falls back to the session\-bus
.B org.freedesktop.ScreenSaver
and
.B org.freedesktop.PowerManagement.Inhibit
interfaces used by GNOME, KDE and other desktops.
.PP
If no assertion option is supplied,
.B \-i
is assumed.  caffeinate holds its assertion until a terminating condition is
reached: the
.B \-t
timeout elapses, the
.B \-w
process exits, the spawned
.I command
exits, or caffeinate is interrupted.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Assertions
.TP
.B \-d
Prevent the display from sleeping.
.TP
.B \-i
Prevent the system from idle sleeping.  This is the default.
.TP
.B \-m
Prevent the disk from idle sleeping.  Accepted for macOS compatibility; Linux
has no distinct disk\-idle assertion, so this is folded into
.BR \-i .
.TP
.B \-s
Prevent the system from sleeping entirely (suspend/hibernate).
.TP
.B \-u
Declare that the user is active.  Asserts a display\-wake for the timeout
duration (defaulting to 5 seconds when no
.B \-t
is given).
.SS Duration
.TP
.BI \-t " seconds"
Hold the assertion for the given number of seconds, then exit.
.TP
.BI \-w " pid"
Hold the assertion until the process with the given pid exits.
.TP
.IR command " [" args ...]
Run
.I command
and hold the assertion until it exits.  caffeinate exits with the command's
exit status.
.SS Other
.TP
.B \-v
Verbose: report which inhibition backends were engaged.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print a usage summary and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print the version and exit.
.SH EXIT STATUS
When a
.I command
is run, caffeinate exits with that command's status (128+signal if it was
killed, 127 if it could not be executed).  Otherwise it exits 0 on normal
completion, or 2 on a command\-line usage error.
.SH EXAMPLES
Keep the system awake until interrupted:
.PP
.RS
.B caffeinate
.RE
.PP
Keep the display awake during a long download:
.PP
.RS
.B caffeinate \-d wget https://example.com/big.iso
.RE
.PP
Prevent suspend for one hour:
.PP
.RS
.B caffeinate \-s \-t 3600
.RE
.PP
Stay awake until a specific process finishes:
.PP
.RS
.B caffeinate \-w $(pgrep \-n rsync)
.RE
.SH NOTES
The locks are taken in login1
.I block
mode, so they stop the machine from sleeping on its own.  They do not stop you
from suspending it deliberately - only the automatic, idle-triggered kind of
sleep is inhibited, which is the whole point of caffeinate.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR systemd-inhibit (1),
.BR loginctl (1),
.BR org.freedesktop.login1 (5)
.SH AUTHOR
A from-scratch, init-system-agnostic take on the macOS caffeinate command.
